claims:
Claims 1. A method for automated wearable assistance, the method comprising: detecting a distress signal from a sensor of a distressed user device; broadcasting a cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) request based on detecting the distress signal from the sensor of the distressed user device; receiving a response to the broadcasted CPR request based on an altered direction of travel of a responding user device; and establishing a connection between the distressed user device and the responding user device. 2. The method of claim 1 , wherein detecting the distress signal from the sensor of the distressed user device further comprises: monitoring a heart rate of the distressed user device based on a biometric sensor. 3. The method of claim 1 , wherein the broadcasted cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) request is sent using ultrasound communication. 4. The method of claim 1 , wherein the broadcasted cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) request further comprises an identifying detail selected from the group consisting of a name of the user in distress, a photograph of the user in distress, and a location of the user in distress. 5. The method of claim 1 , wherein the connection between the distressed user device and the responding user device is established by exchange of electronic handshake using ultrasound communication. 6. The method of claim 1 , wherein the altered direction of travel of the responding user device is towards the distressed user device. 7. The method of claim 1 , wherein the vital sign of the distressed user device is selected from the group consisting of a heart rate value, a blood pressure value, and a body temperature value. 8. The method of claim 1 , further comprising: sending a vital sign of the distressed user device to the responding user device. 9. A computer system for automated smart watch assistance, comprising: one or more processors, one or more computer-readable memories, one or more computer-readable tangible storage medium, and progr